Various cyclic nitrones such as 5,5-dimethyl-1-pyrrolin–N-oxide (DMPO) have been successfully exploited in spin trapping experiments [38–40]. DMPO is effective in trapping alkyl (R

                     ), hydroxyl (

                     OH) and alkoxy (

                     OR) radicals (Fig. 1
                     ), because the presence of the two β-methyl groups hinders the disproportionation of the resulting spin adducts, thus rendering them more stable [41,42] (Fig. 2
                     ).

When sonication starts, radicals form in our experimental conditions. We can detect radical adducts after 5 min of sonication and their concentration in the media increases with time (Fig. 4
                        ). The concentrations reach a plateau between 30 min and 40 min of sonication (Figs. 5 and 6

                        ), indicating that formation and decomposition of adducts are in equilibrium [62]. In a separate experiment, we tracked the decomposition rate of the radicals after sonication (lasted 60 min) stopped. After 105 min, there are no more radicals in the solution in the absence of solids (Fig. 7
                        ).
